{
  "What unit is commonly used to measure electrical energy consumption in households?": "",
  "Amperes based": "",
  "Kilowatt-hours (kWh)": "",
  "Watts, particula": "",
  "Volts, particula": "",
  "Kilowatt-hours (kWh) measure energy consumption over time. One kWh equals the energy used by a 1,000-watt appliance running for one hour, and it is the standard billing unit for residential electricity.": "",
  "What is the relationship between watts and kilowatts?": "",
  "1 kilowatt = 1,000,000 watts": "",
  "1 kilowatt = 100 watts": "",
  "1 kilowatt = 10,000 watts": "",
  "1 kilowatt = 1,000 watts": "",
  "The prefix 'kilo' means one thousand, so one kilowatt equals 1,000 watts. This conversion is essential for energy calculations on the AP Environmental Science exam.": "",
  "If a 100-watt light bulb runs for 10 hours, how much energy does it consume?": "",
  "100 kWh": "",
  "1 kWh": "",
  "10 kWh": "",
  "0.1 kWh": "",
  "Energy = Power x Time. A 100-watt bulb running for 10 hours uses 100 W x 10 h = 1,000 Wh = 1 kWh of electrical energy.": "",
  "What does thermal efficiency of a power plant measure?": "",
  "The cost of fuel per unit of electricity": "",
  "The number of employees needed to operate the plant": "",
  "The temperature inside the plant": "",
  "The percentage of fuel energy converted into useful electrical energy": "",
  "Thermal efficiency is the ratio of useful electrical energy output to total fuel energy input, expressed as a percentage. A plant with 33% efficiency converts one-third of its fuel's energy into electricity.": "",
  "One BTU (British Thermal Unit) is the amount of energy needed to do what?": "",
  "Boil one gallon of water": "",
  "Raise the temperature of one pound of water by one degree Fahrenheit": "",
  "Heat a house for one hour": "",
  "Power a 100-watt bulb for one minute": "",
  "A BTU is defined as the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one pound of water by one degree Fahrenheit. It is a standard unit of energy used in the heating and energy industries.": "",
  "What is the typical thermal efficiency of a coal-fired power plant?": "",
  "About 10-15%": "",
  "About 95-99%": "",
  "About 75-80%": "",
  "About 33-40%": "",
  "Conventional coal-fired power plants typically convert about 33-40% of the chemical energy in coal into electricity. The remaining 60-67% is lost as waste heat, primarily through cooling systems and exhaust gases.": "",
  "How many joules are in one kilowatt-hour?": "",
  "1,000 joules": "",
  "1,000,000 joules": "",
  "3,600 joules": "",
  "3,600,000 joules (3.6 MJ)": "",
  "One kWh = 1,000 watts x 3,600 seconds = 3,600,000 joules (3.6 megajoules). This conversion is important for AP APES calculations involving different energy units.": "",
  "If electricity costs $0.12 per kWh, what is the daily cost of running a 2,000-watt space heater for 8 hours?": "",
  "$2.40": "",
  "$1.92": "",
  "$19.20": "",
  "$0.96": "",
  "Energy used = 2,000 W x 8 h = 16,000 Wh = 16 kWh. Cost = 16 kWh x $0.12/kWh = $1.92 per day.": "",
  "What is the capacity factor of a power plant that produces 600,000 MWh annually and has a maximum rated capacity of 100 MW?": "",
  "About 100%": "",
  "About 68%": "",
  "About 50%": "",
  "About 85%": "",
  "Maximum annual output = 100 MW x 8,760 hours/year = 876,000 MWh. Capacity factor = 600,000/876,000 = 0.685, or about 68%.": "",
  "A gallon of gasoline contains approximately 120,000 BTUs of energy. If a car engine is 25% efficient, how many BTUs of useful work does one gallon provide?": "",
  "90,000 BTUs": "",
  "30,000 BTUs": "",
  "60,000 BTUs": "",
  "120,000 BTUs": "",
  "Useful work = Total energy x Efficiency = 120,000 BTUs x 0.25 = 30,000 BTUs. The remaining 90,000 BTUs are lost as heat through the engine, exhaust, and friction.": "",
  "What is a quad in energy measurement?": "",
  "One quadrillion BTUs (10^15 BTUs), used to measure national and global energy consumption": "",
  "Four kilowatt-hours of electricity when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "A quarter of a megawatt, particularly regarding very based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "Four barrels of oil equivalent when measured under controlled conditions": "",
  "A quad equals one quadrillion (10^15) BTUs and is used to express very large energy quantities at national and global scales. The United States consumes roughly 100 quads of energy per year.": "",
  "What does 'nameplate capacity' mean for a power plant?": "",
  "The maximum rated electrical output a power plant can produce under ideal conditions": "",
  "The total energy the plant will produce over its lifetime": "",
  "The number of customers the plant can serve": "",
  "The brand name printed on the plant's equipment": "",
  "Nameplate capacity is the maximum electrical output a generator can produce as specified by the manufacturer under ideal conditions. Actual output is usually lower due to maintenance, fuel supply, and environmental factors.": "",
  "What is a 'barrel of oil equivalent' (BOE)?": "",
  "The volume of any fuel that fits in a standard oil barrel": "",
  "A unit of energy approximately equal to the energy released by burning one barrel of crude oil, about 6.1 GJ": "",
  "The weight of one barrel of crude oil": "",
  "The cost of one barrel of oil on the global market": "",
  "A barrel of oil equivalent is a unit of energy approximately equal to the thermal energy released by burning one barrel (42 gallons) of crude oil, about 6.1 gigajoules. It allows comparison of different energy sources on a common scale.": "",
  "What is 'peak demand' in electricity generation?": "",
  "The highest price that electricity reaches on the market": "",
  "The lowest level of electricity use during the day": "",
  "The maximum efficiency of a solar panel": "",
  "The maximum level of electricity consumption during a specific time period, typically on hot summer afternoons": "",
  "Peak demand is the greatest amount of electricity consumed at any point during a defined period. Utilities must have enough capacity to meet peak demand, which often occurs on hot summer afternoons when air conditioning use is highest.": "",
  "What is 'energy density' of a fuel?": "",
  "The weight of a fuel per unit volume": "",
  "The number of power plants using a particular fuel": "",
  "The rate at which a fuel burns": "",
  "The amount of energy stored per unit mass or volume of a fuel": "",
  "Energy density measures how much energy is contained in a given mass or volume of fuel. Fuels with high energy density, like uranium and gasoline, pack more energy per kilogram than low-density fuels like wood.": "",
  "What does 'transmission loss' refer to in electricity distribution?": "",
  "The loss of signal in television broadcasting": "",
  "The loss of power when a generator shuts down": "",
  "The energy lost as heat when electricity travels through power lines from generation to consumption": "",
  "The cost of building new transmission lines": "",
  "Transmission losses occur because electrical resistance in power lines converts some electricity to heat. In the U.S., about 5% of electricity is lost during transmission and distribution, which is why high-voltage lines are used to minimize losses.": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'heat rate' for a power plant?": "",
  "The amount of fuel energy (in BTUs) required to generate one kilowatt-hour of electricity": "",
  "The rate of heat rejection to the cooling water": "",
  "The speed at which a power plant heats up": "",
  "The temperature of exhaust gases leaving the plant": "",
  "Heat rate is the inverse of efficiency expressed in BTUs per kWh. A plant with a heat rate of 10,000 BTU/kWh requires 10,000 BTUs of fuel energy to produce 1 kWh of electricity, corresponding to about 34% efficiency.": "",
  "What does 'dispatchable' mean when describing a power source?": "",
  "A power source that can be turned on or off and adjusted to meet demand on command": "",
  "A power source that only operates during emergencies": "",
  "A power source that can be delivered by truck": "",
  "A power source that has been decommissioned": "",
  "Dispatchable power sources, such as natural gas plants and hydroelectric dams, can be ramped up or down as needed to match electricity demand. Unlike intermittent sources like solar and wind, they provide power on demand.": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'insolation' in solar energy calculations?": "",
  "The angle at which sunlight hits a solar panel": "",
  "The insulation material used in solar panels": "",
  "The amount of solar radiation energy received on a given surface area over a specific time period": "",
  "The temperature inside a solar thermal collector": "",
  "Insolation (incoming solar radiation) measures the solar energy received per unit area over a period of time, typically expressed in kWh per square meter per day. It varies by latitude, season, and weather conditions.": "",
  "What does 'per capita energy consumption' mean?": "",
  "The total energy consumed by the capital city of a country": "",
  "The maximum energy a single person can use": "",
  "The cost of energy per household": "",
  "The average energy consumed per person in a given population": "",
  "Per capita energy consumption divides the total energy used by a country or region by its population, providing a measure of average individual energy use that allows comparison between nations of different sizes.": "",
  "A city plans to install a 500 MW solar farm. The region receives an average of 5 peak sun hours per day, and the solar panels have an efficiency of 20%. If the city needs 2,000 MWh of electricity per day, will the solar farm meet this demand?": "",
  "No, it will only produce 1,000 MWh per day": "",
  "Yes, it will produce 2,500 MWh per day, exceeding demand": "",
  "No, it will only produce 500 MWh per day": "",
  "Yes, it will produce exactly 2,000 MWh per day": "",
  "Daily output = 500 MW x 5 hours = 2,500 MWh per day. The nameplate capacity already accounts for panel efficiency, so the farm produces 2,500 MWh, which exceeds the 2,000 MWh daily requirement.": "",
  "A coal plant burns 5,000 tons of coal per day. Each ton of coal contains approximately 20 million BTUs of energy. If the plant operates at 35% efficiency, how many million BTUs of electricity does it produce daily?": "",
  "100,000 million BTUs": "",
  "35,000 million BTUs": "",
  "65,000 million BTUs": "",
  "20,000 million BTUs": "",
  "Total fuel energy = 5,000 tons x 20 million BTUs/ton = 100,000 million BTUs. At 35% efficiency, useful electricity = 100,000 x 0.35 = 35,000 million BTUs per day.": "",
  "A homeowner receives an electricity bill showing 900 kWh of consumption for the month at a rate of $0.15 per kWh. They are considering installing a solar panel system that produces an average of 25 kWh per day. What percentage of their monthly electricity would the solar panels provide?": "",
  "About 55%": "",
  "About 83%": "",
  "About 25%": "",
  "Monthly solar production = 25 kWh/day x 30 days = 750 kWh. Percentage of consumption = 750/900 = 0.833, or about 83% of the household's monthly electricity needs.": "",
  "A wind turbine has a nameplate capacity of 3 MW and a capacity factor of 30%. How much electricity does it produce in one year?": "",
  "26,280 MWh": "",
  "900 MWh": "",
  "3,000 MWh": "",
  "7,884 MWh": "",
  "Annual production = Capacity x Hours in year x Capacity factor = 3 MW x 8,760 hours x 0.30 = 7,884 MWh per year.": "",
  "A natural gas power plant emits 0.4 kg of CO2 per kWh of electricity generated, while a coal plant emits 0.9 kg of CO2 per kWh. If a utility replaces a 500 MW coal plant (capacity factor 70%) with a natural gas plant of equal capacity and capacity factor, how many metric tons of CO2 would be avoided annually?": "",
  "About 3 million metric tons": "",
  "About 100,000 metric tons": "",
  "About 500,000 metric tons": "",
  "About 1.53 million metric tons": "",
  "Annual generation = 500 MW x 8,760 h x 0.70 = 3,066,000 MWh. CO2 reduction per kWh = 0.9 - 0.4 = 0.5 kg. Total reduction = 3,066,000,000 kWh x 0.5 kg/kWh = 1,533,000,000 kg = about 1.53 million metric tons.": "",
  "A household uses 10,000 kWh of electricity per year. If the average U.S. electricity generation emits 0.4 kg of CO2 per kWh, and the household switches to 100% solar power, how many metric tons of CO2 emissions would be eliminated annually?": "",
  "40 metric tons": "",
  "0.4 metric tons": "",
  "400 metric tons": "",
  "4 metric tons": "",
  "CO2 eliminated = 10,000 kWh x 0.4 kg/kWh = 4,000 kg = 4 metric tons of CO2 per year. Solar power produces no direct CO2 emissions during electricity generation.": "",
  "A power plant burns natural gas with an energy content of 1,000 BTUs per cubic foot. The plant uses 50 million cubic feet of gas per day and operates at 45% efficiency. How many kWh of electricity does it produce daily? (1 kWh = 3,412 BTUs)": "",
  "About 3.3 million kWh": "",
  "About 50 million kWh": "",
  "About 6.6 million kWh": "",
  "About 14.6 million kWh": "",
  "Total fuel energy = 50,000,000 ft3 x 1,000 BTU/ft3 = 50 billion BTUs. Useful energy at 45% efficiency = 50 billion x 0.45 = 22.5 billion BTUs. Electricity = 22,500,000,000 / 3,412 = about 6.6 million kWh.": "",
  "A country consumes 100 quads of energy per year and has a population of 330 million people. If per capita energy consumption needs to be reduced by 20% to meet climate targets, how many quads must total consumption decrease by, assuming the population remains constant?": "",
  "20 quads": "",
  "10 quads": "",
  "33 quads": "",
  "50 quads": "",
  "A 20% reduction in per capita consumption with a constant population means a 20% reduction in total consumption. 20% of 100 quads = 20 quads, bringing total consumption to 80 quads per year.": "",
  "An electric vehicle uses 0.3 kWh of electricity per mile, while a gasoline car uses 0.04 gallons per mile. If electricity costs $0.12/kWh and gasoline costs $3.50/gallon, how much does a driver save per 1,000 miles by switching to the electric vehicle?": "",
  "$50": "",
  "$104": "",
  "$36": "",
  "$140": "",
  "EV cost per 1,000 miles = 1,000 x 0.3 kWh x $0.12 = $36. Gas car cost = 1,000 x 0.04 gal x $3.50 = $140. Savings = $140 - $36 = $104 per 1,000 miles.": "",
  "A proposed hydroelectric dam would have a capacity of 200 MW with a capacity factor of 50%. The dam would flood 5,000 hectares of forest. A solar farm alternative would require 4 hectares per MW with a capacity factor of 25%. Comparing equivalent annual energy production, which option uses less land?": "",
  "The solar farm uses less land": "",
  "There is not enough information to determine the answer": "",
  "Both options use exactly the same amount of land": "",
  "The hydroelectric dam uses less land": "",
  "Dam annual output = 200 MW x 0.50 = 100 MW effective, using 5,000 hectares. For equivalent solar output: need 100/0.25 = 400 MW nameplate solar capacity. Solar land = 400 MW x 4 ha/MW = 1,600 hectares. The solar farm uses significantly less land (1,600 vs. 5,000 hectares).": ""
}